Sheet1.Description: Lie back on a flat bench holding a dumbbell in each hand. Your palms should face your feet. Push the dumbbells up until your arms are fully extended and slowly lower them back after a short pause. Keep your arms close to your body during the exercise.

Set an adjustable bench to an incline of 15-30 degrees. Lie back on the bench and hold a barbell with a grip slightly wider than shoulder-width. Lower the bar to your upper chest, pause, then press it back to the starting position.

Set an adjustable bench to a decline of 15-30 degrees. Lie back on the bench and hold a barbell with a grip slightly wider than shoulder-width. Lower the bar to your lower chest, pause, then press it back to the starting position.

Lie back on a flat bench holding a dumbbell in each hand with your arms extended above you, palms facing each other. Lower your arms out to the sides in an arc motion, keeping a slight bend in your elbows. When your arms are parallel to the floor, reverse the motion to return to the starting position.

Grab the pull-up bar with your palms facing away (pull-up) or towards you (chin-up). Hang with your arms fully extended. Pull yourself up until your chin is above the bar, then lower yourself back to the starting position.
Sit down at a lat pulldown machine and grab the bar with a wide grip. Pull the bar down to your chest while keeping your torso stationary. Slowly return the bar to the starting position.
Hold a dumbbell in each hand, bend at the waist with your knees slightly bent. Keep your back straight and row the dumbbells to your sides, then lower them back down.

Stand with your feet hip-width apart, bend at your hips and knees to grab the barbell. Lift the barbell by extending your hips and knees until you are standing straight. Lower the barbell back down with control.

Place one knee and hand on a bench for support. With the opposite hand, hold a dumbbell and let it hang towards the floor. Pull the dumbbell to your hip, then lower it back down.
Stand or sit holding a dumbbell in each hand at shoulder height. Press the dumbbells overhead until your arms are fully extended, then lower them back to the starting position.

Lie back on a flat bench holding a barbell with a narrow grip. Lower the bar to your chest while keeping your elbows close to your body, then press it back up.

Sit on the ground with your upper back resting against a bench and a barbell across your hips. Thrust your hips upwards until your body forms a straight line from your shoulders to your knees. Lower your hips back down.

Stand between two cable machines with the pulleys set high. Grab the handles with your arms extended. Pull the handles down and together in front of your body, then slowly return to the starting position.

Start in a downward dog position with your hips raised. Lower your head towards the ground by bending your elbows, then push back up.

Sheet1.Exercise: Standing on One Leg with Eyes Closed
Sheet1.Description: Stand on one leg and close your eyes, maintaining your balance by engaging your core and leg muscles. Hold the position for as long as possible and repeat on the other leg.
